title: Industrial tenants are heading to the Central West
text:
Aerial view of Sydney's central west where demand is high for industrial properties
Industrial property is under the spotlight with sales transactions and stronger leasing rental deals concluded as investors see the sector benefiting from low supply and high demand, particularly near new infrastructure project.
One of the latest deals was by DEXUS Wholesale Property Fund (DWPF) which exchanged conditional contracts for the sale of Acacia Gate Industrial Estate in Brisbane for $21.6 million.
This follows the sale of 2 Costello Place, Seven Hills, Sydney last week for $14.9 million and the recent sale of the Melbourne International Airfreight Centre for $23.9 million.
This sale completes the fund's recent industrial divestment strategy, which focused on disposing three smaller, non-core industrial assets at an attractive point in the market cycle.
Advertisement The three properties were acquired by DWPF in 2010 as part of the 13 asset Colonial Direct Property Investment Fund industrial portfolio.
DWPF fund manager, Penny Ransom, said the three divestments reflects the strategy to recycle capital out of non-core assets at attractive points in the cycle.
"We remain focused on delivering on our development pipeline and on acquisition opportunities where we can add value over the long term," Ms Ransom said.
Industrial leasing momentum is also forecast to improve in Sydney's mature Central West precinct in the next 12 months, according to JLL's director of industrial,NSW, Orlando Macielâ€‹.
The Central West area effectively commences around Enfield and across to Rosehill, extending south to Greenacre and north to Homebush.
"Given that larger existing vacancy in Western Sydney was virtually depleted following more than 125,000 square metres of leasing activity directly related to building damage from the April storm, some occupiers are now scouring the Central West," Mr Maciel said.
"A number of major tenants and owner occupiers are understood to be chasing sites in the strategically central location, led by third party logistics companies with parcel handling requirements."
Mr Maciel said this has been evident recently with the marketing of one of the last available pre-lease sites in the Central West, at 37-39 Wentworth Street, Greenacre, which can accommodate 5000 square metres to 20,000 square metre users and is adjacent to the recently completed Enfield Intermodal Logistics Centre.
JLL director of industrial research, Nick Crothers, said that while research data shows that average prime grade net face rents in the Central West precinct have grown very little since mid-2009 and average $132 per square metre per annum, it has increased recently due to the lower availability of space and occupiers relocating from nearby residential growth zones.
